Certainly! Let’s take a simple example where a microservice handles user authentication. The key is to define an abstraction (interface) for the authentication mechanism and then implement it separately. This allows you to swap out the authentication provider without affecting the business logic.

Example in pseudocode:

// Define the abstraction
interface IAuthService {
    bool authenticate(String username, String password);
}

// Concrete implementation, e.g., verifying against a database
class DatabaseAuthService implements IAuthService {
    bool authenticate(String username, String password) {
        // Query the user table and validate credentials
        return database.verifyUser(username, password);
    }
}

// Another possible implementation, e.g., using an external OAuth provider
class OAuthAuthService implements IAuthService {
    bool authenticate(String username, String password) {
        // Call an external API and verify the token
        return oauthProvider.verify(username, password);
    }
}

// Business logic uses the abstraction rather than a specific implementation
class AuthController {
    private IAuthService authService;

    // Dependency injection via constructor
    AuthController(IAuthService authService) {
        this.authService = authService;
    }

    void login(String username, String password) {
        if(authService.authenticate(username, password)) {
            // Proceed with login
            print("Login successful");
        } else {
            print("Invalid credentials");
        }
    }
}

// Example of wiring up dependencies
// In a production environment, a DI container could handle this
IAuthService authService = new DatabaseAuthService();
AuthController controller = new AuthController(authService);
controller.login("user1", "password123");

This pseudocode illustrates the dependency inversion principle well. The AuthController depends on the IAuthService interface rather than a specific implementation. This decoupling allows you to easily inject a different authentication mechanism if needed, thereby enhancing maintainability and flexibility in your microservices architecture.
